INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('9541d57496ed82fac116586ef48bbec1cdeae6e0e3904e68ff6ba107e7ed82d6','End Semester','Basics of Mechanical Engineering','ME24101','1','2024','Q.1(a)','Using vector analysis, prove that the moment of a force F in 3D space, with respect to an arbitrary axis defined in the Cartesian coordinate system, remains constant regardless of the point chosen on the arbitrary axis.','\\text{Using vector analysis, prove that the moment of a force } \\mathbf{F} \\text{ in 3D space, with respect to an arbitrary axis defined in the Cartesian coordinate system, remains constant regardless of the point chosen on the arbitrary axis.}','To prove that the moment of a force F about an axis is independent of the point chosen on that axis, we define the axis by a unit vector u passing through point O. Let P be a point on the line of action of F. The moment about O is Mo = r x F, where r is the position vector from O to P. The moment about the axis u is defined as the projection of Mo onto u, given by M_axis = (r x F) · u. Let O\' be another arbitrary point on the axis. The new position vector is r\' = r - a, where a is the vector from O to O\'. The new moment about the axis is M\'_axis = (r\' x F) · u = ((r - a) x F) · u. Expanding using the distributive property, we get (r x F) · u - (a x F) · u. Since a is parallel to u, the triple scalar product (a x F) · u vanishes because the vector (a x F) is perpendicular to a (and thus perpendicular to u). Therefore, M\'_axis = M_axis, proving the value is constant.','1. \\text{Let the axis be defined by a unit vector } \\mathbf{u} \\text{ passing through point } O. \\text{ Let } P \\text{ be a point on the line of action of force } \\mathbf{F}. \\\\ 2. \\text{The moment of } \\mathbf{F} \\text{ about point } O \\text{ is } \\mathbf{M}_O = \\mathbf{r} \\times \\mathbf{F}. \\\\ 3. \\text{The moment of } \\mathbf{F} \\text{ about the axis } \\mathbf{u} \\text{ is the scalar projection: } M_{axis} = (\\mathbf{r} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 4. \\text{Consider another point } O\' \\text{ on the same axis. Let } \\mathbf{a} \\text{ be the vector from } O \\text{ to } O\'. \\text{ Since } O\' \\text{ is on the axis, } \\mathbf{a} = k\\mathbf{u} \\text{ for some scalar } k. \\\\ 5. \\text{The new position vector is } \\mathbf{r}\' = \\mathbf{r} - \\mathbf{a}. \\\\ 6. \\text{The moment about the axis with respect to } O\' \\text{ is: } M\'_{axis} = (\\mathbf{r}\' \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 7. \\text{Substitute } \\mathbf{r}\' = \\mathbf{r} - \\mathbf{a}: M\'_{axis} = ((\\mathbf{r} - \\mathbf{a}) \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 8. \\text{By the distributive property of the cross product: } M\'_{axis} = (\\mathbf{r} \\times \\mathbf{F} - \\mathbf{a} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 9. \\text{Using the dot product property: } M\'_{axis} = (\\mathbf{r} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u} - (\\mathbf{a} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 10. \\text{Since } \\mathbf{a} = k\\mathbf{u}, \\text{ the term } (\\mathbf{a} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u} = (k\\mathbf{u} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 11. \\text{The triple scalar product } (\\mathbf{u} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u} \\text{ is zero because } \\mathbf{u} \\times \\mathbf{F} \\text{ is orthogonal to } \\mathbf{u}. \\\\ 12. \\text{Thus, } M\'_{axis} = M_{axis}.','M_{axis} = (\\mathbf{r} \\times \\mathbf{F}) \\cdot \\mathbf{u} = \\text{constant}','["Moment", "Statics", "Vectors"]','derivation','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('11cb53aaf4690b1e4bbb22118fc259901059d22352c7d61aa5463ec2a7309ea5','End Semester','Basics of Mechanical Engineering','ME24101','1','2024','Q.1(a)','Discuss the transformation of a determinate truss into an indeterminate one, accompanied by mathematical reasoning. Additionally, illustrate the process with appropriate diagrams.','\\text{Discuss the transformation of a determinate truss into an indeterminate one, accompanied by mathematical reasoning.}','1. Define determinate truss criteria: A truss is statically determinate if the number of members (m) plus the number of reactions (r) equals twice the number of joints (j), expressed as m + r = 2j. 2. Define indeterminate transformation: A truss becomes statically indeterminate when it possesses redundant members or reactions such that m + r > 2j. 3. Mathematical reasoning: In a determinate truss, all internal forces and reaction forces can be solved using static equilibrium equations alone. When m + r > 2j, the system has \'n\' redundant constraints where n = (m + r) - 2j. These extra constraints make it impossible to solve for forces using only static equilibrium, requiring compatibility equations based on material deformation. 4. Example: A simple triangular truss (m=3, j=3, r=3) satisfies m + r = 2j (3+3=6, 2*3=6). Adding a fourth member inside the triangle creates a redundant path, resulting in m=4, j=3, r=3. Here, 4+3=7, while 2*3=6. Since 7 > 6, the degree of indeterminacy is 1.','\\text{A planar truss is statically determinate if: } m + r = 2j \\text{, where } m \\text{ is the number of members, } r \\text{ is the number of external reactions, and } j \\text{ is the number of joints.} \\\\ \\text{A truss is transformed into statically indeterminate when redundant members are added or external support constraints are increased, such that: } m + r > 2j. \\\\ \\text{The degree of indeterminacy (i) is given by: } i = (m + r) - 2j. \\\\ \\text{Example: Consider a triangular truss with } m=3, j=3, r=3. \\text{ Eq: } 3+3 = 2(3) = 6. \\text{ This is determinate.} \\\\ \\text{Adding one diagonal member: } m=4, j=3, r=3. \\text{ Eq: } 4+3 = 7 \\neq 2(3)=6. \\\\ \\text{Since } 7 > 6, i = 1, \\text{ the structure is statically indeterminate of the first degree.}','i = (m + r) - 2j, \\text{ where } i > 0 \\text{ for indeterminacy.}','["Indeterminacy", "Trusses"]','theoretical/derivation','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','4','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('d9c17fe02bb4c451165ac9a821b2e659b2cba5b59c2c23a59ad17eea95bf2ad5','End Semester','Basics of Mechanical Engineering','ME24101','3','2023','Q.3(a)','For a simple screw jack, derive the expressions for effort applied at the circumference of spindle and force applied at the end of the lever, when the load is hoisted upwards.','\\text{For a simple screw jack, derive the expressions for effort applied at the circumference of spindle (P) and force applied at the end of the lever (P}_1\\text{) when the load (W) is hoisted upwards.}','1. Assumptions: The screw jack is modeled as an inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder. Friction is accounted for by the coefficient of friction (mu) and the helix angle (alpha). 2. Force equilibrium: For lifting a load W, the effort P acting at the circumference of the spindle must overcome the component of the load acting down the plane and the frictional resistance. 3. Geometry: Helix angle alpha is given by tan(alpha) = pitch / (pi * mean diameter). 4. Force resolution: Resolving forces horizontally and vertically results in the expression P = W * tan(alpha + phi), where phi is the friction angle. 5. Lever calculation: By the principle of moments, the force P1 at the end of the lever of length L relates to P by the ratio of the radius of the spindle to the length of the lever.','1. \\text{Assumptions: Consider a screw with pitch } p, \\text{ mean diameter } d, \\text{ and helix angle } \\alpha = \\tan^{-1}(\\frac{p}{\\pi d}). \\text{ Let } \\mu = \\tan \\phi \\text{ be the coefficient of friction}. \\\\ 2. \\text{Force analysis: For hoisting the load } W, \\text{ the horizontal effort } P \\text{ required at the circumference is given by: } P = W \\tan(\\alpha + \\phi). \\\\ 3. \\text{Expanding the tangent identity: } P = W \\frac{\\tan \\alpha + \\tan \\phi}{1 - \\tan \\alpha \\tan \\phi}. \\\\ 4. \\text{Substituting } \\tan \\alpha = \\frac{p}{\\pi d} \\text{ and } \\tan \\phi = \\mu: P = W \\frac{\\frac{p}{\\pi d} + \\mu}{1 - \\mu \\frac{p}{\\pi d}}. \\\\ 5. \\text{Force at the end of the lever: Let } L \\text{ be the lever length and } r = d/2 \\text{ be the spindle radius. By the principle of moments, } P_1 \\cdot L = P \\cdot r. \\\\ 6. \\text{Therefore, } P_1 = P \\cdot \\frac{d}{2L} = W \\left( \\frac{p + \\mu \\pi d}{\\pi d - \\mu p} \\right) \\frac{d}{2L}.','P = W \\tan(\\alpha + \\phi) \\text{ and } P_1 = \\frac{W \\cdot d}{2L} \\tan(\\alpha + \\phi)','["Friction", "Mechanics", "Screw Jack"]','derivation','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);